Here is an example of synchronous and asynchronous code in Java using one thread:
Synchronous code:
```
public class SynchronousExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Start");
        try {
            Thread.sleep(2000);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        System.out.println("End");
    }
}
```
This code will run in a single thread and will print "Start" then sleep for 2 seconds, then print "End".
Asynchronous code using Callable and Future:
```
import java.util.concurrent.Callable;
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.util.concurrent.Future;
public class AsynchronousExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        System.out.println("Start");
        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();
        Callable<String> callable = () -> {
            Thread.sleep(2000);
            return "End";
        };
        Future<String> future = executor.submit(callable);
        executor.shutdown();
        System.out.println(future.get());
    }
}
```
This code will also run in a single thread but it will print "Start" immediately and will print "End" after 2 seconds by using callable and future which allows the code to be run in an asynchronous way.
