Yes, it is possible to perform atmospheric correction of remote sensing images with Google Earth Engine (GEE).
GEE provides a built-in algorithm called "Atmospheric Correction" which is a implementation of the 6S radiative transfer model. This algorithm can be applied to Landsat 4-8, Sentinel-2 and MODIS images to correct for atmospheric effects such as scattering and absorption of light by the atmosphere.
Here is an example of how to use the "Atmospheric Correction" algorithm on a Landsat 8 image in GEE:
```php
// import the Landsat 8 image
var image = ee.Image('LANDSAT/LC08/C01/T1_TOA/LC08_044034_20170608');
// define the atmospheric correction parameters
var atmosCorrect = ee.Algorithms.Landsat.TOA({
  'image': image,
  'elevation': ee.Image("USGS/SRTMGL1_003"),
});
// display the corrected image
Map.addLayer(atmosCorrect, {bands: ['B4', 'B3', 'B2'], min: 0, max: 0.3});
```
This code will import a Landsat 8 image, apply the atmospheric correction algorithm, and display the corrected image on the map.
It's important to note that, the accuracy of the results can depend on the quality of the data and the method used, therefore, it's recommended to consult the data provider documentation and know the data quality and limitations before starting the analysis.
